ce:section.ce:para:
For the raw materials used to construct SIWEs, most SIWEs use chemicals throughout, which may lead to potential environmental pollution and ecological risks. Only two SIWEs were constructed from biomass derivatives: mushroom [44] and wood [41]. However, their water evaporation rates were relatively low, which were 1.48 and 1.45 kg m-2h−1, respectively. Their STCEs were also relatively low, which were 78 % and 91.3 %, respectively (as shown in 
                           Table S1
                        ). Compared to these two types of SIWEs, ESCDs-wood improved the water evaporation rate by 98.6 % and 102.8 %, and STCE by 76.38 % and 50.69 %, respectively. At the same time, since ESCDs-wood was constructed without the use of any chemicals, it had the advantage of being greener, more sustainable and environmentally friendly than most SIWEs.

Notably, compared with other chemical CDs or carbon-based STCMs, the most obvious difference of ESCD was its formation of Ca-self-doping. Was the functionalization of CDs by Ca-doping a solar-thermal conversion performance enhancement? Therefore, this study hypothesized that the Ca-doping of ESCD was a key factor for efficient solar-thermal conversion, and the effect of Ca-doping on the solar-thermal conversion performance of CDs was further investigated (
                           Section 3.5 and 3.6
                        ).
